  <h2>Why scarcity works — and why the knockouts supercharge it</h2>

  <p>Scarcity is one of the best-documented principles in the psychology of persuasion. When something appears limited, fleeting, or about to disappear, people assign it more value and feel a stronger pull to act before the window shuts. It is why "only a few left" and "offer ends tonight" are everywhere in retail: the fear of missing out overrides slower, more careful judgment. Most of the time these deadlines are invented — the sale will quietly return next week — and once you know that, they lose some of their grip.</p>

  <p>The knockout stage is more dangerous precisely because its scarcity is partly real. A team genuinely can be eliminated in a single game; this genuinely may be the last time it plays in the tournament. So "last chance to back them" is not a fabricated sale deadline — it is, in a narrow and literal sense, true, and that kernel of truth makes the urgency far more persuasive than any marketing department could manufacture on its own. The format supplies the authentic drama of win-or-go-home, and the messaging simply attaches the bet to it. You are not being lied to about the deadline. You are being encouraged to confuse a true fact about <em>when</em> you can bet with a false implication about <em>whether</em> and <em>how much</em> you should.</p>

